Opening Sequence: Sensory Overload and Vision

Simeon experiences overwhelming sensory horror in complete darkness
He perceives physical sensations in disturbing, alienated ways (body parts as "meat," "sack," etc.)
Ancient words form in a near-elvish tongue with the message: "Salvation lies beyond world's edge"
Simeon regains bodily awareness through pain and discomfort
His eyes open to see a mycelium-like network of white, iridescent light
The mycelia pulses like a heartbeat, spreading through walls and air
At the center of the network, threads converge into a large, slowly pulsing light
Simeon speaks his first words: "My God"
He weeps, burying his face in his arms
The entire sensory overload sequence repeats identically
The lights at the ends of the mycelial network extinguish permanently

The Cold Water Chamber

Grant douses Simeon with frigid water
Simeon claws at himself while Grant pulls him up
Grant drags Simeon through lamp-lit hallways
Simeon sees ghostly white strands and black tendrils spreading through the air and along walls
A black thread touches Simeon's shoulder, causing numbness
He squeezes his own shoulder hard enough to create pain and warmth
Grant shoves Simeon into a guest room

First Encounter with Anne

Anne, a young red-haired servant in Eleanor colors, orders Simeon to bathe
Her hands and face appear to glow to Simeon's altered vision
Simeon notices the gold and black ring on his finger
He attempts repeatedly to remove the ring but fails
The ring burns his skin when he tries to pry it off
A black tendril touches Simeon's shoulder, causing him to panic
Simeon crashes into the wardrobe, knocking Anne to the ground
Anne threatens to accuse him of rape if he doesn't comply
Simeon points out the black tendrils, which Anne cannot see
Anne tries to pull Simeon toward the bath but he resists
He slams his elbow against the marble wall
Anne leaves, frustrated, passing harmlessly through a black tendril

Bonnie's Arrival

Bonnie enters and finds Simeon in distress
She appears older and matronly with graying hair
Simeon embraces her while still seeing visions through closed eyes
Three children peek through the doorway
Bonnie sends her son Jonah and daughters away with Anne
One child asks why Simeon smells funny
Simeon learns Bonnie named her son after his friend Jonah
Bonnie helps Simeon undress and directs him behind a partition to bathe

The Bath Conversation

In the bath, the white trails temporarily disappear above Simeon
Simeon tries to explain his visions to Bonnie
He describes white fiber-like strands and black squirming things around lamps
He asks about the ring and repeats the cryptic message about salvation
Simeon asks about his half-brother (the future king)
Bonnie confirms the prince is fine and with Simeon's mother
Simeon mentions weapons, synapsids, and elves confusedly
The master tailor arrives and Bonnie is dismissed
Bonnie tells Simeon that Anne will attend him and welcomes him to House Eleanor
Simeon asks why Bonnie is there, but she ignores him and leaves

The Tailor's Visit

The elderly master tailor with a hooked nose confronts Simeon
Simeon realizes he's naked and doesn't remember when that happened
The tailor threatens to report Simeon to Lady Eleanor for wasting time
Simeon defiantly states Eleanor already tried to kill him
He hints at knowing something more terrible than synapsids
The tailor notices the ring on Simeon's finger
Simeon stands for measurements, ducking under ghostly branches
The tailor takes measurements with a white cord and black wax
The tailor leaves, passing through a black tendril

Evening in the Guest Room

Simeon recognizes the room as similar to his old guest quarters
He dresses in nightclothes and collapses on the bed
Anne brings food and asks if he needs anything
Simeon requests Father Genwald but learns Eleanor has banned the priest
He then requests his mother, Mistress Lancaster
Anne realizes Simeon is "that Simeon" - a Lancaster
Anne shares her backstory about her mother becoming a concubine

Anne's Confession and Seduction Attempt

Simeon explains he joined the church because of Princess Eleanor's singing
He reveals he betrayed Eleanor's secret and someone named Cynthia was taken
Anne reveals Cynthia lied about having a child with Jonathan
Anne's mother spread the rumor, leading to Cynthia's shunning
Anne's mother eventually killed herself while working for House Eleanor
Anne states she'll never forgive Cynthia but that Lady Eleanor has grown crueler
Anne removes her dress, revealing her body
She begs Simeon to save her from her situation
Simeon closes his eyes but feels her approach the bed
He feels fire in his veins and reaches toward her
Bonnie enters and catches them
Anne quickly claims Simeon attacked her
Bonnie sees through the lie and orders Anne to take a bath and cool off
Anne leaves, humiliated and angry

Late Night with Bonnie

Bonnie enters with her toddler daughter Sarah clinging to her skirt
She explains she and Hugh became the baby's retainers in Simeon's absence
Simeon nearly repeats his mistake with Jonah by almost succumbing to Anne
Sarah stares at Simeon with furrowed brow
Bonnie introduces Sarah to Simeon
Sarah shyly states her name and hides in Bonnie's arm
Simeon compliments Sarah's beautiful eyes
The two adults talk late into the evening about their lives
Bonnie describes her marriage to Hugh and Jonah joining the guard
Sarah falls asleep on Bonnie's lap as the sun rises

Morning Preparations

Simeon asks if he'll see his half-brother
Bonnie says he'll see him at the council meeting but warns him not to approach
She warns that guards will attack anyone, even Lady Eleanor, who threatens the prince
Bonnie leaves with sleeping Sarah as Simeon loses consciousness
Simeon dreams or hallucinates an earthy mushroom smell
Anne wakes him gently, apologizing for the previous night
She looks exhausted with bags under her eyes
Anne sets out breakfast (manna) and informs him his new clothes are in the wardrobe
She offers to wait in the hallway if he needs anything

Final Preparations and Resolution

Simeon attempts to grasp the ghostly white threads but his fingers pass through
He examines his hands, noting shallow lines and calluses only on his writing fingers
He discovers fine velvet clothing with golden vines and the Eleanor winged creature emblem
Simeon asks for his robes and learns Lady Eleanor had them burned
He angrily slams the wardrobe, protesting that he's a monk, not her possession
Anne pleads that Eleanor will punish her if he doesn't wear the clothes
Simeon decides to "play the game" and find Eleanor's weakness
He declares the house will collapse like a mushroom cap in drought
Anne helps him dress, lacing the coat's frogs with focused attention
Simeon vows to unravel Eleanor's web just as he did with Cynthia
